by Combine Interuniversal » Fri Oct 01, 2021 5:01 pm

Ideal countries aren't necessarily perfect (Mary Sue) polities, Hatsunia. Anyways, applying character terms to political bodies is a very weird practice. A perfect country is either deliberate, making them a utopia, or the result of bad writing. In the latter's case it is the author failing to deliver the consequences of a nation's policy or diplomatic action, or failing to come up with a believable history and circumstances for a utopian society.

For the former, it's a form of literature whose purpose is to portray a better state of society that we should all strive to achieve. A good utopian nation is one that tells a story of a society which has overcome the problems it faces in an engaging sort of way, entailing a demand for novel or at least creative and semi-original takes to what is a very saturated niche of the NationStates forums.

A re-occurring cliché is seeing something (very obviously) based on fictional scenarios being called unrealistic. It's as much a cop-out meta response akin to disliking a leader in an AL thread for being "anime artstyle".

by Hatsunia » Fri Oct 01, 2021 5:30 pm

Combine Interuniversal wrote:failing to come up with a believable history and circumstances for a utopian society.

In recent months, that is exactly what Hatsunia's lore was criticized for - that there was no struggle involved in obtaining a egalitarian society, and that the government just decided to support gender and racial equality out of pure idealism so on a meta level, social issues wouldn't become "deeply rooted." Some people offered constructive criticism by saying that Hatsunese society would realistically have been more bigoted in the past, but overcame it through protests and other forms of activism and resulting government reforms, thus I revised the lore to be where it is today. And it does seem more meaningful that way.

I've always maintained that having a nation that constantly talks about how perfect and amazing it is is what makes a nation a MarySuetopia tbh.

Like it's the difference between 'My nation is a developed first-world nation with a fairly high standard of living' and 'My nation is the most developed nation in the entire world and it's all so perfect here, everyone wishes they could live here, our largest city makes places like New York, Tokyo, Paris, or Beijing look like a joke and has ten times as economic power as any of those cities and was voted the greatest city in the world in 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, and 2020. We have no crime whatsoever because of how well-funded everything is and everyone's lives are so great, so why would anyone want to commit any crimes? It makes no sense.'
